   "abstract": "Singh examines how Canadian law enforcement applies algorithmic technologies that connect facial images to scattered public and private databases to identify people and predict future trends. The central argument is that these surveillance tools have been authorized through Supreme Court jurisprudence and common-law authorities rather than by legislation passed by Parliament, leaving Charter rights exposed and consequences falling disproportionately on people of colour. Singh calls on legislators to enact dedicated law governing the use of these technologies.",
